Accuracy = TP+TN / TP+TN+FP+FN
Sensitivity = TP / TP+FN
Specificity = TN / TN+FP

Another time. I was walking with my best friend. As we came to an intersection I said "I've never witnessed a car accident." As the last word came out of my mouth a cab screeched on its brakes and rear-ended the car in front of us.
He never came back to school. I heard he has permanent screws in his ankle.

He was on the roof with the two kids who would pick on me. They were installing a ham radio antenna. While clearing debris, Juan stepped on a skylight. His friends warned him but he stood on it and crashed through.

Everyone else and I, got up to investigate. As I got closer there was glass all over the ground. Juan was laying stomach down and crying for his mom. His left leg was mangled broken in 3 places and his foot was in the wrong direction.

That day I was in the computer animation station. While I was working a loud crash of glass interrupted the silence of the classroom. I turned around and saw Juan near the teachers island. He teetered for a moment and fell over.
One morning I woke up and hoped that he would break his leg and not come into school again.
A month and two other courses later him and his friends continually harassed me. Throwing stuff and trying to trip me etc.

I ended up in the AV course with a heavy set twin named Juan (his brother was Bubba). Juan was an asshole. He told me that he wanted to fight me. I told him I didn't want to fight. That didn't matter to him and he would pick on me relentlessly, trying to get me to fight him.
Every two weeks you do a new course and are paired with a new partner to learn with.

One of the first that I recall, I was in 9th grade. I was in a class that had multiple mini courses in it, each had something to do with technology or mechanics. There was a car in the classroom for learning how it works. The room was like a warehouse, tall 20' ceilings.
I have had some amazing coincidences in life. Different than Deja Vu, though that has happened a lot too.
Besides the gash in my knee. I had Jeep tire tread bruises on the front of my legs.
The man in the BMW was an emotional wreck. He was chain smoking and shaking like crazy.
The guy in the Jeep was on his way to the beach with two women. He asked if this was that first time I was hit by a car. He said he had been hit several times.
The EMT recognized my mom because she was rear ended the previous week at the same intersection.

I had a deep gash on one knee. I asked the EMT if I was looking at my knee cap. He denied it and put some peroxide on it and bandaged me up. I asked him again because it sure looked like it. He caved and said it was, he just didn't want to freak me out.

My brother witnessed it. He ran and told my parents I got hit by a truck. A neighbour saw it too and called 911. The ambulance arrived moments after my relieved parents, who immediately thought I was killed by a semi.

Somehow my legs didn't break but my bike was bent to hell and my head put a dent in the door of the BMW. I wiggled my toes and pulled the bike from between my legs and walked to the corner and sat with my head in my hands.

A Jeep lost its patience and made the right turn around the BMW, screeching his tires. He didn't see me going around the BMW. He hit the front tire of my bike and I slammed against the BMW and watched in horror as my bike and legs were run over by the large knobby tires.

I was almost to the corner where I could get back on the sidewalk. A man in a BMW didn't see me while making a very tight right turn. Blocking my passage. He saw me just in time and honked. I waved and went around him on his driver side.
I was riding my bike. I had almost collided with a boy in the neighborhood that I was playing with. I avoided him and ended up on a one way street, facing the wrong way.
When I was 11 I was run over by a Jeep.

Fortunately I've recognized and worked hard to break that cycle. I've learned what not to do.
I know my parents love me and that they're also a product of their environment and did what they believe is right.
because being different often isn't a choice.
But it's also what makes me cry hearing about a loss of life of someone for being different.
It is a lifetime of shit like that, that make me doubt myself. Make me feel less than.
Or that by all intensive purposes most people might consider me to be a good person.
It didn't matter that I hadn't gotten into alcohol and drugs. Or that I was moderately successful given my roadblocks and being uneducated.
That sparked a 3 page letter from my mom telling me how disappointed she was in me and that she had failed as a mother.
It wasn't until my parents moved out of state that I told my parents that I never believed.
I'm a terrible liar. I don't like being lied to, and lies only make the truth harder to hear. But I had to lie about my faith to survive.
My father's faith made it ok to abuse me for not being able to recall scriptures. Though the threat of abuse makes it hard to concentrate.
My mothers devotion to the rules and belief of her religion are what kept her in place. And distorted her answers into inhumane ones.
This was not an answer I expected. A dark hole I didn't know I could even tumble down.
I also once spoke to her about the abuse I received and her response was "well your dad shouldn't have had kids."
I asked her why she stayed and she said he paid his price by not being able to read the watchtower to the congregation for 3 months.
My mother stayed with my father even after attempted murder.
I could have easily taken a similar road, but introspection helped me set rules and recognise how wrong the actions against me were.
Because if I questioned it I would get beaten.
I get triggered by seeing abuse of women and children in movies. I also lose strength and my voice when debating religion with others.
To this day I regret not calling. Though in my father's altered state, he might have ended up killing us all that day.
My mom was dropped, she told me to call the cops. My dad yelled at me not to. I collapsed, I didn't know what to do.
Had I not walked in on it, I wouldn't have a mom today.
I watched my father struggle with alcohol. While drunk he tried to kill my mom by lifting her off the ground strangling her by the neck.
I don't understand how anyone can be hurt and think it's their job to pass on more hurt. Instead of "I don't like it, I shouldn't do it."
Experiences and handling them are unique to everyone. I get that.
Everyone is built up or torn down by environment. Some, like me learn what not to do from their parents. Others reciprocate it.
Maybe it's delusions of grandeur? Though I honestly would rather the world be a better place than take a credit for it.
I find myself getting upset that I'm not more than I am. Or that I can't solve the problems of the world.
Unfortunately so is depression.
I try to continually improve myself. Introspection is a big part of who I am due to being beaten into believing that everything is my fault.
My dad eventually apologized when I brought home a paycheck that was bigger than his.
My father would tell me that I would get nowhere "playing games" and that programming is a waste of time.
He introduced me to IRC and MUDs. Which sparked my interest in my career. I owe where I am to him.
I met my lifelong best friend in church at 14. He told me the elders son said I was a weirdo. Fortunately he was also a weirdo.
My parents never once stood up for me. Ironically I have been physically abused by my father for physically defending myself.
I knew what it was like to be hated from all angles for just being me.
I didn't buy into the hate that my parents had for LGBTQ people. Instead I sympathised.
If I gained anything it was to recognize my struggle in others who were "different."
I took solace in video games and computers but hungered for friends. I became an introvert by circumstance.
So those friendships wouldn't last.
I resorted to not revealing my religion at school to keep acquaintances. I wasn't allowed to hang out with many of them after school.
Over years and instances to trap me, it worked. I had no chance in the my-word-against-his game.
When I was 8-9 a family joined our congregation. He was jealous that a girl liked me. He led a crusade to turn the other JW kids against me.
It also set me up for the isolation I've carried my entire life.
I was also sent to daycare until third grade where I was bullied and tormented. This possibly contributed to my lack of judgement.
I wasn't and I'm still not a very good judge of character. Friendship was more important than the personalities of the friends I made.
I had a couple friends growing up that were "worldly" that my parents eventually allowed because neglect is easier than participation.
It didn't help that I would lose friends or be told I couldn't be friends with someone when their parents discovered my parents religion.
I was also constantly stuffed like a foie gras goose that "worldly people" don't care about me.
Instead of introspection or empathy or change. I would get: No other family will ever love you like we do, you'd only end up somewhere worse
I would get broken by them and say things like "I wish I had another family" it was also what I prayed for every night.
I was also lead to believe that being mentally demeaned and physically abused was a part of growing up that everyone experienced.
My parents belief that the world would come to a halt at any given moment surpassed the forethought that being educated can make life better
It's one of my many life decisions that I regret. Though I understand why I made the decision.
I asked what it meant and they hypothesised that I was bored and needed more work. I declined.
Afterwards my parents were called in to discuss the results. They said I was gifted and wanted to put me in gate classes.
A picture says a thousand words and if I were her skin I'd want to escape too.
I've done the math and that's a one night stand I regret.
